{"cursor":"4132","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox person |image = laceyatthelibrary.png |caption = Robert Lacey at\nSurrey County Library's speaking event in 2012 |Img_size\n| birth_date = occupation =British historian and biographer yearsactive =\n| 1964âpresent first_published = 1971\n}} 'Robert Lacey' (born 3 January 1944) is a British historian and\nbiographer. He is the author of a number of bestselling biographies,\nincluding those of Henry Ford [http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.htm-\nl?res=9B0DE4DF173BF93BA15755C0A961948260&scp=2&sq=Robert%20Lacey%20best%20se-\nllers&st=cse New York Times, 28 June 1987] and Queen Elizabeth II, as\nwell as works of popular history.\n\nLaceyâs 1981 work The Kingdom and its 2009 follow-up Inside the Kingdom have now\nboth been cited as standard study texts for the diplomatic community working\ninside the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia. This has led to Lacey being employed by\nAmerican Television networks, ABC [http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Books/inside-kingdom-robert-\nlacey/story?id=8835259 abcnews.go.com â EXCERPT: Inside the Kingdom] and\nPBS as a commentator on the subject.\n\nIn 2009 Lacey made the controversial documentary âRehab for Terrorists?:\nCan terrorists be rehabilitated with kindness?â for the âNowâ show for the\nPBS channel.\n\nLacey is also ABC's [[Good Morning America]] Royal commentator and was in London\nfor the channel covering the Royal Wedding of Prince William and Kate Middleton.\nHe was also seen on the BBCâs late evening coverage of the event. David\nBrancaccio said: \"In Saudi Arabia, Robert Lacey had the kind of access most\njournalists only dream of.\" [http://www.pbs.org/cove-\nmedia/http/PBS_CP_NOW/70/650/transcript.html â PBS Transcript: Rehab for\nTerrorists?]\n\nLacey is an alumnus of Bristol Grammar School and a graduate of Selwyn College\nin the University of Cambridge where he earned a B.A. in 1967, a diploma of\neducation in 1967, and an M.A. in 1970. http://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Aristocrats.html?id=qp-\nUKm46MlkC&redir_esc=y He began his writing career as a journalist on the\n[[Illustrated London News]], and later [[The Sunday\nTimes]]. [http://ebookstore.sony.com/author/437/30/43730.html Sony ebook\nwebsite]\n","linknr":139,"url":"Robert_Lacey","recorded":1376418608,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Robert_Lacey&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Robert_Lacey&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Lacey","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Robert_Lacey_(disambiguation)","/wiki/File:Laceyatthelibrary.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/30/Laceyatthelibrary.png/220px-Laceyatthelibrary.png","/wiki/Henry_Ford","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Queen_Elizabeth_II","/wiki/American_Broadcasting_Company","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Public_Broadcasting_Service","/wiki/Good_Morning_America","/wiki/BBC","/wiki/David_Brancaccio","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Bristol_Grammar_School","/wiki/Selwyn_College,_Cambridge","/wiki/University_of_Cambridge","/wiki/Bachelor_of_Arts","/wiki/Diploma_of_education","/wiki/Master_of_